<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900827-0070</DOCNO><DOCID>900827-0070.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Kellogg Asks Court   In Towns to Block Action   Against Its Cereal Ads</HL><DATE>08/27/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   K</CO><IN>FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)</IN><LP>   BATTLE CREEK, Mich. -- Kellogg Co. said it asked a federalcourt in Iowa to block the Iowa attorney general from actingagainst the company's health claims in advertisements forSpecial K, 40 + Bran Flakes and Frosted Flakes cereals.   Kellogg said it filed its suit to end what it views as&quot;harassment&quot; by Iowa Attorney General Thomas J. Miller andthe attorneys general of seven other states. The officialsraised questions two years ago about the Kellogg ads. Sincethen, Kellogg said it has engaged in &quot;long and fruitlessdiscussions&quot; with the attorneys general and providedthousands of pages of documents substantiating its claims.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We think it's time to bring this to an end and let thecourts decide,&quot; said Joseph M. Stewart, senior vice presidentfor corporate affairs. &quot;We stand behind our advertising. . .. They (the attorneys general) continue to say ouradvertising is misleading.&quot;   Mr. Miller, the Iowa attorney general, couldn't be reachedfor comment. Kellogg said the attorneys general hadn'tproduced a single consumer complaint or scientific study tosupport their allegations.   Kellogg said the issue involves its claims that Special Kis a high-protein cereal and can help dieters or exercisers&quot;keep the muscle, lose the fat;&quot; that 40 + Bran Flakes isrich in fiber and iron and is beneficial to those 40 andolder and that Frosted Flakes is &quot;good for you&quot; and has lesssugar than many snack foods.</TEXT></DOC>